TY  - JOUR
T1  - Hyperturbulence and the Emergence of Type 5 Environments
AU  - McCann, Joseph E.
AU  - Selsky, John
Y1  - 1984/07/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1984.4279678
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1984.4279678
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 460
EP  - 470
VL  - 9
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper explores what happens when complexity and change exceed the collective adaptive capacity of members populating an environment?a condition called hyperturbulence. The prospect of hyperturbulence generates an adaptive response by members called partitioning, which attempts to allocate and protect scarce capacity. Two types of domains emerge within the environment: the social enclave and the social vortex. Both domains are described, examples of each given, and implications for future research noted.
AB  - This paper explores what happens when complexity and change exceed the collective adaptive capacity of members populating an environment?a condition called hyperturbulence. The prospect of hyperturbulence generates an adaptive response by members called partitioning, which attempts to allocate and protect scarce capacity. Two types of domains emerge within the environment: the social enclave and the social vortex. Both domains are described, examples of each given, and implications for future research noted.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1984.4279678
